title: For Sale/Trade:  Czech VZ24 Mauser -- great condition!!!! Make Offer
location: Elizabeth, WV, Belpre, OH, Parkersburg, West Virginia
postcontent:
UPDATE: just to clarify, the caliber is indeed 7.65 x 53. 

I have an early model Czech VZ.24 Mauser. This gun is truly loaded with history (search google to find out). It is also revered by many (including Nazi soldiers of WWII, who used them in Stalingrad after capturing Czechoslovakian factories and also sent them to their Romanian allies) to be better than their own Mauser K98. As it was made in 1924, it is generally believed to have inspired the German design of the Karabiner 98k. These rifles appear to be moderately rare and few are around today as compared to the K98. To make it more rare, it is a Bolivian Contract rifle with the Condor bird marking. Only 101,000 of these were ever contracted, caliber 7.65 (7.65 x 53), to be used in the Chaco War. This rifle has NO IMPORT MARKINGs, and as Bolivia has not released these rifles for import, it is likely a vet bring-back. It also has numerous markings indicating that it was made by the Czechs and also accepted into their army (Z within a circle; "E" in front of a rampant lion) before being contracted out. I have been told by numerous experts that this gun features many components of a very early VZ24.
It is a great rifle in better condition than most (nearly any) I have seen. The action is smooth and cycles rounds beautifully. It functions and shoots just fine, if you're not into just letting it sit. This is one of the best bolt actions I have ever seen. The only reason I am even considering selling it is because I have always wanted an M1 Garand, and this will help me buy one.

Make an offer -- but please no lowballers! This is a quality Mauser worth much more than a Mosin Nagant (I know, I own one). It's hard to get a quality VZ24 anymore.

Thank you very much for looking!

P.S. Please ask for pics! The pics have high MB and Armslist cannot process it.

A. Excellent. Go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment to pick it up.

Q. Are there any other fees, in addition to the price and taxes? NICS, background check, etc?
A. No.

Q. What is the tax rate?
A. 9.5% (WA only, of course, not applicable for out-of-state shipments)

Q. Where are you located?
A. Queen Anne neighborhood in Seattle.

Q. Can we meet in Burien on Monday morning?
A. No, FFL requirements are that the transfers happen at a licensed location. Also, the only times you can come over are the appointments that you can reserve on the site. No other time slots are available.

Q. I see you carry Savage rifles. Can you find me MKII FV-SR?
A. No. Please see here for what I can or cannot do: http://www.preciseshooter.com/NotInStock.aspx

Q. Do you take trades?
A. Sometimes. However:
a) firearms only,
b) they need to be our of current production (I can get new ones at wholesale prices), or you have to offer them to me at well below wholesale
c) I do not resell the trades, so they should fit my personal interests (which only include military as well as highly accurate, competition guns - no self defense guns like Glocks, M&Ps, XD*, and the like)
d) the exchange rate should be fair (see here for more: http://www.preciseshooter.com/blog/PriceGuide.aspx

Q. Is the price firm? Will you take XXX (70% of the asking price)?
A. The price is firm.

Q. Can you help me mount a scope/replace a trigger/fix a feeding problem?
A. Sorry, I do not do gunsmithing.

Q. Will you ship?
A. Yes - go to www.preciseshooter.com -> How to buy and read the section for buying outside Seattle area.

title: For Sale:  Russian Saiga AK47 (converted & Parkerized)
location: Harris County/North Columbus, Columbus, GA, Georgia
postcontent:
This is a Russian-made Saiga AK, that has been Parkerized, and converted to legally use standard high-capacity magazines, several years ago by Mike Hill over at Bullseye Bluing.
The conversion included the installation of Dinzags bullet guide, and the G2 trigger group.
The Saigas are manufactured in Russia at the same factory that produces Russia's military AK47's, and are widely acknowledged as among the highest quality AK variants there are.
 This rifle is still virtually brand new, has only been fired a handful of times, and has been flawlessly reliable (as always, I have no problems with a test fire, if you have someplace safe and convenient to shoot).
In case you haven't heard, as of July 16,2014, El Presidente has banned the importation of all Russian-made weapons, including the Saigas, in retalition for Russia's aggression in the Ukraine.
Predictably, prices are rising rapidly, and existing supplies are drying up fast, with most vendors completely sold out (or about to). The likelyhood of this ban ever being rescinded is unlikely in the extreme, and Saigas will very possibly go the same route as other banned AK's, like the Chinese Polytechs, that now run $1800+.
Included are two 30-round magazines, and a couple boxes of ammo (both magazines and ammo are still widely available and fairly inexpensive).
Asking $1000. Cash preferred, but trades considered, specifically a quality 1911, or CZ75. 
The photo shows the rifle with a Choate one-piece stock (which is the most functional, ergonomic AK stock I've ever used), or I can switch it to the standard buttstock and pistol grip that's seen in the photo. Pick one.
Also, I'm the original owner of the rifle, and have my Georgia carry permit, so everything's good on my end.
Thanks for looking.......

title: For Sale:  Russian Saiga AK47 (converted)
location: Harris County/ N. Columbus, Columbus, GA, Georgia
postcontent:
This is a Russian-made Saiga AK, that has been Parkerized, and converted to legally use standard high-capacity magazines, several years ago by Mike Hill over at Bullseye Bluing.
The conversion included the installation of Dinzags bullet guide, and the G2 trigger group.
The Saigas are manufactured in Russia at the same factory that produces Russia's military AK47's, and are widely acknowledged as among the highest quality AK variants there are.
 This rifle is still virtually brand new, has only been fired a handful of times, and has been flawlessly reliable (as always, I have no problems with a test fire, if you have someplace safe and convenient to shoot).
In case you haven't heard, as of July 16,2014, El Presidente has banned the importation of all Russian-made weapons, including the Saigas, in retalition for Russia's aggression in the Ukraine.
Predictably, prices are rising rapidly, and existing supplies are drying up fast, with most vendors completely sold out (or about to). The likelyhood of this ban ever being rescinded is unlikely in the extreme, and Saigas will very possibly go the same route as other banned AK's, like the Chinese Polytechs, that now run $1800+.
Included are two 30-round magazines, and a couple boxes of ammo (both magazines and ammo are still widely available and fairly inexpensive).
Asking $1000. Cash preferred, but trades considered, specifically a quality 1911, or CZ75. 
The photo shows the rifle with a Choate one-piece stock (which is the most functional,ergonomic AK stock I've ever used), or I can switch it to the standard buttstock and pistol grip that's seen in the photo. Pick one.
Also, I'm the original owner of the rifle, and have my Georgia carry permit, so everything's good on my end.
Thanks for looking.......

title: For Sale:  wheat penny
postcontent:
The 1922 "plain" or "no d" can be produced from four different die pairs. Die Pairs #1, #3 and #4 produce either 
a "weak D" or a "No D". Die Pair #2, which is the most desirable of the four die pairs, always produces a "No D". 

In 1922 only the Denver Mint was responsible for producing Lincoln Cents. Both Mints were busy producing 
millions of Silver Dollars. No nickels, dimes, quarters, or half dollars were produced in 1922. The creation of all 
four die pairs was the result of the Denver Mint running out of usable dies with thousands of cents needed to be 
struck to fill their quota. 

Die Pairs #1, #3 and #4 were the result of "mint grease", which is a combination of dirt, metal, and oil, filling the 
area of the mintmark. Mint grease would fill the mintmark gradually, resulting in different levels of "weakness". It 
is believed that the mint grease would fall out, then refill creating a cycle of normal D's, broken D's, weak D's, and 
no D's. When looking at circulated examples of 1922 D's, keep in mind that the mintmark could have simply be 
worn from use. Die Pairs #1, #3 and #4 have "weak reverses" because they were struck with worn reverse dies. 

Die Pair #2 is not believed to be the result of "mint grease". A pair of dies that were creating 1922 D's clashed 
together. The clash resulted in damage to both the obverse and reverse die. The reverse die was badly 
damaged, and replaced with a newer less worn die. The obverse die was reworked by a mint employee who 
erased all traces of the D mintmark while repairing and polishing the die. The result is a worn obverse die with no 
trace of a mintmark and a strong reverse die. 

All 1922 weak D or No D coins fall into one of 7 categories:
1. Die Pair #1 Weak D (Weak Reverse)
2. Die Pair #1 No D (Weak Reverse)
3. Die Pair #2 No D (Strong Reverse) also called 1922 Plain **************************
4. Die Pair #3 Weak D (Weak Reverse)
5. Die Pair #3 No D (Weak Reverse)
6. Die Pair #4 Weak D (Weak Reverse)
7. Die Pair #4 No D (Weak Reverse)

email or txt REDACTED 
will trade for a good lever action, sixgun, silver or gold bullion or gold jewelry
make an offer!!
